					of probability became well established and even dominant. According to this &nbsp;
					deﬁnition, if one repeats the random experiment N times, and if NA denotes the &nbsp;
					number of trials at which the event A occurs, the ratio NA/N should be close to the &nbsp;
					probability P(A) when N is large. This is an informal statement of the law of large &nbsp;
