					9.1 Independent&nbsp;Events &nbsp;
					Throughout this chapter, we consider a probability space (Ω, A, P). If A, B&nbsp;∈ A &nbsp;
					are two events, we say that A and B are independent if &nbsp;
					P(A ∩ B) = P(A)P(B). &nbsp;
					If P(B) &gt; 0, we can interpret this deﬁnition by saying that the conditional &nbsp;
					probability &nbsp;
					P(A ∩ B) &nbsp;
					P(A | B) (d=ef) &nbsp;
					P(B) &nbsp;
					is equal to P(A): knowing that B holds gives no information on whether A holds or &nbsp;
					not (and the roles of A and B can be interchanged). &nbsp;
					Examples &nbsp;
					2
					(i) Throwing two dice : Ω = {1, 2, . . . , 6} , P({ω}) = 1/36 for every ω ∈ Ω. The &nbsp;
					events A = {6} × {1, 2, . . . , 6} (6 at the ﬁrst trial) and B = {1, 2, . . . , 6} × {6} &nbsp;
					(6 at the second trial) are independent. In fact the probability measure P has &nbsp;
					been constructed so that any event concerning the ﬁrst trial is independent of &nbsp;
					any event concerning the second trial. &nbsp;
					(ii) Throwing one die : Ω = {1, 2, . . . , 6}, P({ω}) = 1/6 for every ω ∈ Ω. The &nbsp;
					events A = {1, 2} and B = {1, 3, 5} are independent. &nbsp;
