					9.2 Independence&nbsp;for σ-Fields and Random Variables &nbsp;
					We say that B is a sub-σ-ﬁeld of A if B is a σ-ﬁeld and B ⊂ A. Roughly speaking, &nbsp;
					a sub-σ-ﬁeld B corresponds to some partial information in the probability space, &nbsp;
					namely the information given by knowing which events in B have occurred (for &nbsp;
					instance, if B = σ(X) where X is a random variable, the corresponding information &nbsp;
					is just the value of X). This suggests that the most general notion of independence &nbsp;
					is that of independent sub-σ-ﬁelds: informally, two sub-σ-ﬁelds B and Bꢃ will &nbsp;
					be independent if knowing which events of B have occurred does not give any &nbsp;
					information on the occurrence of events of Bꢃ, and conversely. We make this more &nbsp;
					precise in the following deﬁnition. &nbsp;
					Deﬁnition 9.3&nbsp;Let B1, . . . , Bn be n sub-σ-ﬁelds of A. We say that B1, . . . , Bn are &nbsp;
					independent if, for every A1 ∈ B1, A2 ∈ B2, . . . , An ∈ Bn, &nbsp;
					P(A1 ∩ A2 ∩ . . . ∩ An) = P(A1) P(A2) . . . P(An). &nbsp;
					&nbsp;
