					A Few Facts from Functional Analysis &nbsp;
					In this appendix, we recall some basic results about Hilbert spaces and Banach &nbsp;
					spaces, which are used in the text. Proofs of these results can be found in [22] or in &nbsp;
					most textbooks on functional analysis. &nbsp;
					Normed Linear Spaces and Banach Spaces &nbsp;
					Let E be a linear space over the ﬁeld R. A norm on E is a mapping x → ꢆxꢆ from &nbsp;
					E into R that satisﬁes the following properties: &nbsp;
					+
					• ꢆx + yꢆ ≤ ꢆxꢆ + ꢆyꢆ for every x, y&nbsp;∈ E (triangle inequality); &nbsp;
					• ꢆaxꢆ = |a| ꢆxꢆ for every x ∈ E and a ∈ R; &nbsp;
					• ꢆxꢆ = 0 if and only if x = 0. &nbsp;
					One says that (E, ꢆ · ꢆ) is a normed linear space. The norm induces a distance d &nbsp;
					on E, which is deﬁned by the formula &nbsp;
					d(x, y) = ꢆx − yꢆ. &nbsp;
					The normed linear space (E, ꢆ · ꢆ) is called a Banach space if it is complete for the &nbsp;
					distance induced by the norm. In other words, if (xn)n∈N is a Cauchy sequence in &nbsp;
					E, meaning that &nbsp;
					lim ꢆxm − xnꢆ = 0, &nbsp;
					m,n→∞ &nbsp;
					there exists x ∈ E such that the sequence (xn)n∈N converges to x. &nbsp;
